Written to `tools/title-loop/docs/3-a5a0dca/feedback.md`. Here's a summary of the analysis:

## Four failures, three root causes

**Pattern 1 — Substring dedup removes the correct multi-line join** (ARAYES SHRAK, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS, Baked Eggs)

The dedup rule discards a longer candidate when a shorter substring has `rawScore >= longer`. The problem: partial titles ("ARAYES", "SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK") score *at least as high* as the complete joins in embedding space, because the semantic signal of "recipe title" is fully present in the partial. The full join adds tokens that don't increase title similarity. So the dedup reliably destroys the correct answer, especially when the title is OCR-split across two lines. The Baked Eggs case is the worst: after the join is deduped away, `& Coriander` in isolation scores too low to survive threshold, returning nothing at all.

**Pattern 2 — Position bonus raises the threshold above the second title** (FINNISH FLATBREADS)

`FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` appears at position 67% of the document, getting no position boost. `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` is at 37%, getting a ~7.5% boost. That raised best-score lifts the threshold (`bestScore * 0.8`) just high enough to cut the second title before the multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) can fire.

**Cross-cutting theme**: `firstStructuralHeading` bonus and ALL_CAPS bonuses are applied during scoring but *completely ignored* during deduplication, which uses rawScore only. This means a candidate can be correctly identified as the structural title heading, then silently discarded anyway.
