preferring the shorter substring over the more complete multi-word heading.\n   - The fix would be to avoid this substring-based dedup when the longer text is actually the full title.\n\nNow looking at the second example with \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"—the title spans two lines, with the first line being \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" and the second being \"& Coriander\".\n\nChecking if the first line passes the hard filters: it's 42 characters long, so that passes. It's not an ingredient, number, or metadata. For the garbled text check, I'm counting the vowels in the letters-only version to see if the vowel ratio suggests it's legitimate text. The \"& Coriander\" candidate passes the garbled text filter since it contains no problematic short words and meets the length requirements, so it's also valid as a single line. Checking the garbled filter logic for \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" - there's no period followed by a letter, so that passes, but I need to verify the word-by-word validation where lowercase words longer than 2 characters would fail it. Tomato\"(T), \"Sauce\"(S). All pass.\n   - Hmm but \"& Coriander\" - let me think about whether this could be a problem with the 2-line join. \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" - length = 54 chars, passes.\n   - Wait, the text file shows line 1 as \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" and line 2 as \"& Coriander\". Then line 3 is a long paragraph. So the 2-line join should happen.\n   - Let me check the `isLikelyGarbled` on the joined string more carefully. The vowel ratio looks fine at around 0.43, and when I split it into words like \"Baked\", \"Eggs\", \"with\", \"Feta\", \"Harissa\", \"Tomato\", \"Sauce\", \"&\", \"Coriander\", none of them trigger the garbled word check since they're either too long or don't match the pattern of lowercase short words. So that should pass too.\n   - Now for the actual scoring: since th