ed an empty string, which suggests something else is filtering them out.\n\nLooking at the garbled text check, it's rejecting lines that start with lowercase letters, and \"&\" definitely doesn't match that pattern—so \"& Coriander\" might be getting caught by a different validation rule, possibly the one checking if text starts with a letter or valid character.\n\nBut the real issue is the deduplication logic: when we have the longer combined title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" and the shorter \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\", the dedup rule sees that the shorter one is contained within the longer one and removes the shorter candidate, keeping only the longer version. \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\". But I'm getting an empty string instead, which suggests either \"& Coriander\" isn't making it into the selected candidates, or something else is filtering it out. Let me check the hard filters — \"& Coriander\" is 11 characters, so it passes the length requirement. Maybe the issue is that the recipe body text contains a higher-scoring candidate that's dominating the selection process.\n\nLooking at the actual lines in the file, most of them get filtered out: line 19 starts lowercase so it's marked as garbled, line 4 is metadata, lines 5-16 are ingredients that either fail the ingredient check or start with numbers. So I'm still unclear why the final result is empty.\n\nWait, I think I see it now. The `buildCandidates` function applies `passesHardFilters` before adding anything. For the title \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" - that's 54 characters, well under the 80 character limit. But I need to check the garbled word logic more carefully on each word in that title.\n\nActually, looking at the scoring phase, \"& Coriander\" as a standalone candidate would score very low on title similarity, so it'd likely get filtered out by the threshold. The dedup logic would then replace